{"/service/ndnp/scu/batch_scu_kiwi_ver03/data/sn86063760/00529041263/1923091901/0328.xml":{"full_text":"THE MANNING TIMES\nEntered at the Poatolflce at Manning as Second-Claaa Matter.\nAppelt St Shope, Proprietors.\n_t\nPublished Every Wednesday\nSubscription Rates $2.00 per year in Advance\nMANNING, S. C. WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 19,1923\nTHE TURNER COUNTY PLAN\n-o\nWe are publishing several letters this week from\nmembers of the party who spent several clays in Turner\nCounty, Ga., recently. These letters are highly interest\ning from several viewpoints. These men believe that Clar\nendon County can adopt this plan of diversified farming\nand put Clarendon on the map of the United States as a\nbanner agricultural county. Several of th& members of\nthe party seem to think that the plan should hardly be at\ntempted unless done on rather an elaborate scale, while\nothers advocate the starting of the plan with just what the\nfarmer has on hand. Either of the above plans would\nhave to be left to the individual. v\nThe success of the hog, cow and hen program will de\npend on the co-operation of every citizen of Clarendon\nCounty? It can be put across, but it will take work to do\nit. There is no such a thing as getting \u201crich\u2019* the first\nyear, nor the second year, nor the third year\u2014it will take\nseveral years of hard work and self-denial to put the far\nmer on a self-sustaining basis.\nBy all means let us get together and put the plan into\noperation just as quick as possible. We believe that every\none will gladly do their share in putting it across.\nCOW, HOG AND HEN\u201d PROGRAM\n(Continued from page one)\nof the county is cultivated by small\nfarmers. All of whom are white.\nClarendon has a distinct advantage\never Turner in that we have more\nmoney crops, more timber and richer\nsoils.\nYours very truly,\nG. T. Floyd.\nManning, S. C., Sept. 14, 1923.\nMy impressions of Turner County,\nGeorgia, are very definite ones. It\nwas a backward, wire-grass county\nwith few negroes and a fair soil, but\nnot as good as ours. Few nice school\nbuildings and other evidences of prog\nress.\nCotton and peanuts have been the\nonly real crops. Some watermelons\nand canteloupes have be n planted,\nbut the returns were uncertain. They\nhad no tobacco, and When the boll\nweevil got the cotton the county was\nin a bad fix\u2014really worse off than\nwe were.\nA little more than two years ago a\nfew men, realizing the desperate sit\nuation facing the county, established\na.crcamery and began to urge a diver\nsification program. Now one-third of\nthe farmers of the whole county are\nfurnishing cream to the Creamery\nand they are shipping hogs and chick\nens every month.\nWe talked with farmers who were\nfurnishing crea,.:, raising hogs and\nchickens, and they all talked in the\nhighest terms of the plan an<f expect\nto continue it. We talked to various\nfarmers who had no cows and were\ndoing the old time farming of cotton\nand peanuts, and every one said that\nthey expect to commence this winter\nmilking cows. If the farmers of the\ncounty, generally and unanimously,\nfavof the proposition as they do there\nit is obliged to be a good one and one\nthat would be profitable for us to fol\nlow.\nWe talked to their bankers, and\nother business men and the Clerk 01\nCourt and they all said the county is\nimproving rapidly.\nTurner county farmors generally\nhave not made the mistake of buying\na lot of pure-blood cattle, building big\nred bams, getting cows without feed\nin hand for them, and attempting to\nsubstitute livestock for money crops,\nbut they are raising live stock and\nother money clops.\nI feel certain that if every farmer\nwill provide a pasture, milk a few\ncows,-raise hogs and chickens, and do\nthis without any expense, or prac\ntically no expense for purchase of\nfood, or expense of equipment, then\nthe farm expense can practically be\npaid and the money crops will be\nlargely net profit. When this happens\nwe will be prosperous,\nWe have a better soil, better peo\nple, are better eqiupped, -nd have a\nbetter county than^hey have, but if\nI farming conditions remain for five\nyears the same in the two counties\nthat they are now then they will bt\nso far ahead of us that tvj will not b\u00bb\nable to see their dust. V\nI am glad that there is a spirit cf\noptimism in our'cqpnty and a great\ner unity than usual. I am hopeful\nover the outlook for real solid pros\nperity. Let\u2019s ge'; together on one\nplan and work it.\nYour i truly,\nC .arlten DuRant.\nManning, S. C., Sept. 17, 1923. i\nEditor The Times:\nPlease allow me to express through!\nyou#paper my thanks to the Board of\nTrade, to. County Agent Hast, and to\nthe others who r-ade it possible for\na party of fifteen t go down into Tur\nner County, Geort ia, last week and\ninvestigate their \u201ct.iw, Hog and Hen\u201d\nplan of getting ahead of the bo'.l wee\nvil.\nWe had a delightful trip,by auto\nmobile, visited the farms,* talked with\nthe farmers themselves, saw their\ncattle, hogs and poultry; looked over\ntheir creamery, hatchery, marketing\nbureau, etc., and came away convinc\ned .that Turner County will never\nagain be wholly dependent upon cot\nton for her money crop. In three\nyears| with no tumult and\nshouting, just taking the grade cattle\nand hogs and poultry that they had\non hand, introducing better stock as\nthey were able, they have worked out\na plan of living in which cotton plays\nbut a small part. And their plan has\nsucceeded because of the remarkable\nspirit of oe-operation that exists be\ntween- the farmers, merchants, bank\ners, and their county newspaper.\nSome members of our party, dis\nliking small beginnings and hating in\nnovations, were heard to say that\nClarendon County was better off than\nTurner. In one sense this is true,\nsince Clarendon has more improved\nlands, adapted to more diversified\ncrops than Turner. But if we con\n(Continued on uage seven)\nalarLraricicunnnnnnrinrinnnnnr\n\u2019s Autumn Sports\nand Travel Coats\n\nWith or without fur-collars\nUnusually smart styles in three pop\nular priced groups to select from.\n_ Group 1.\u2014Straight and slim in line, these\nmodels are made of the new plaided fabrics in\nthe most faVored colors, are silk lined throughout,\nand luxuriously finished with a convertible collar\nof Korean fox.\nGroup 2.\u2014Attractive loose back coats develop\ned from imported mixtures, and silk lined\nthroughout. Richly topped by a collar of Korean\nfox dyed red fox color, or American opposum.\nGroup 3.\u2014Sports and travel coats fashioned\nfrom imported tweeds or from smart striped fab\nrics in the softest, loveliest tones. Beautifully\ntailored and finished. Straight and slim in line,\nwith convertible collar of self material.\n.y\nSole Agents for Betty Wales Wash Dresses.\nRIFF NESS:\n\u201cSELLS FOR LESS\u201d Manning, S. C.\nOur store will be closed tomorrow on account of\nJewish Holiday.\nALL GOOD ROADS LEAD TO\nThe Leading Trading Centre of Eastern Carolina.\nIt has always held this position and its progressive business men are deter\nmined that it shall retain this standard.\nHERE\u2019S THE PROOF\n1. It provides you a ready market at highest prices for your cotton, grain, dairy products,\npoultry, vegetables and timber.\n2. It anticipated the return of prosperity and its merchants have amply prepared to take\ncare of your needs by laying in large stocks of quality merchandise at prices that will\nmerit your patronage.\n3. It has six strong banks under conservative and experienced management, assuring safety\nfor your deposits.\n4. Its theatres provide entertainment of the highest class for the enjoyment of the entire\nfamily.\n5. The spirit of the \u201cGamecock City\u201d was never more alive than it is today. Hospitality,\nFriendship and Service are its dominant characteristics. Come and share these with us.\nAgricultural and Trade Information Gladly Given at the Board of Trade.","height":"25032","width":"17600"}}
